The management of electronic transport rules (METR) provides a means for transport user systems to obtain machine-interpretable, publicly available, transport-related, authoritative information for the use of surface transport facilities to better provide safe, efficient, sustainable, comfortable, and equitable transport services.

 

The scope of METR includes both rules that are relatively static (e.g., static speed limits) as well as those that are dynamic (e.g., variable speed limits, signalized intersections). However, where appropriate, METR incorporates existing standards (e.g., ISO/TS 19091 for signalized intersections).

Strictly speaking, the "installer" is responsible for posting the traffic control device, but the traffic control device can be left in a state that does not display a rule to the public (e.g., e.g., the traffic control device can be covered or in the case of a message sign left blank). The "implementer" is responsible for activating the rule, which can consist of removing a cover or posting a message on a sign. In many instances, the two responsibilities are combined and from the perspective of METR both roles are outside the METR system. As such, the ISO 24315 series discusses these two sets of responsibilities as a single role.

The installer is responsible for posting the traffic control device, but the traffic control device can be left in a state that does not display a rule to the public (e.g., e.g., the traffic control device can be covered or in the case of a message sign left blank). The "implementer" is responsible for activating the rule, which can consist of removing a cover or posting a message on a sign. In many instances, the two responsibilities are combined and from the perspective of METR both activities are outside the METR system. As such, while the ISO 24315 series recognizes the potential existence of a separate rule implementer, its responsibilities are grouped into the installer enterprise object to simplify discussions.

The installer (3.3.1.13) is responsible for posting traffic control devices and can also serve as a rule implementer, if authorized by its jurisdictional entity. However, an installer can also leave a traffic control device in an unobservable (3.2.3.5) state (e.g., the traffic control device can be covered or in the case of a message sign left blank). In this case, a separate rule implementer can be made responsible for implementing the rule (e.g., removing a cover or posting a message on a sign). While this document defines the concept of an installer, METR does not have any formal inputs or outputs related to the installer.

The installer (3.3.1.13) is responsible for posting conventional traffic control devices and can also serve as a rule implementer (3.3.1.22), if authorized by its jurisdictional entity (3.1.7). A large governmental body (i.e., a jurisdictional entity) can assign multiple responsible legal authorities for different areas, different purposes, or both. For example, New York City can assign its Department of Transportation the responsibility to create and maintain static locations where vehicles must stop (e.g., typically deployed using fixed stop signs) throughout the city and assign each Precinct of its Police Department with the authority to create and maintain temporary stop locations (e.g., perhaps through hand-held signs or signals).

A simple jurisdictional entity can have a single responsible legal authority that also serves other roles. For example, the owner of a small shop can act as both the jurisdictional entity and the sole responsible legal authority to issue accessible parking restrictions for the small parking lot.

For example, the owner of a small shop can act as the jurisdictional entity, the rule maker, the translator, and the rule approver for issuing accessible parking restrictions for the small parking lot.

A complex jurisdictional entity can assign multiple responsible legal authorities for different areas, different purposes, or both. For example, New York City can assign its Department of Transportation the responsibility to create and maintain static and temporary stop sign locations throughout the city and assign each Precinct of its Police Department with the authority to create and maintain temporary stop sign locations only within their respective precincts.

A complex jurisdictional entity can designate multiple rule makers, each assigned for different areas, different purposes, or both. For example, New York City can assign its department of transportation the responsibility to create and maintain static and temporary stop sign locations throughout the city and assign each precinct of its police department with the authority to create and maintain temporary stop sign locations only within their respective precincts.

A complex jurisdictional entity can designate multiple rule makers, each assigned for different areas, different purposes, or both. For example, the State of New York can adopt a highway code that assigns its department of transportation the responsibility to create and maintain rules for motorways and allows local jurisdictions to create and maintain additional rules. Based on its authority, New York City can assign its department of transportation the responsibility to create and maintain static and temporary stop sign locations throughout the city, assign each precinct of its police department with the authority to create and maintain temporary stop sign locations only within their respective precincts, and assign land owners the responsibility to designate parking spaces for those with disabilities.
